Linux Commands Practice Report
📌 Objective
To learn and practice 15 essential Linux commands used for navigation, file management, system monitoring, and networking.
1. ls (List Directory Contents)
Description:
Displays files and directories in the current location.
Command:  ls
Example Output: Documents  Downloads  file.txt
2. cd (Change Directory)
Description:
Used to move between directories.
Command: cd Documents
Example Output: Directory change successfully and move into the Document folder.
3. pwd (Print Working Directory)
Description:
Shows the current directory path.
Command: pwd
Example Output: /home/kali/Documents
4. mkdir (Make Directory)
Description:
Creates a new directory.
Command: mkdir test_folder
Example Output: (No output, folder created)
5. rm (Remove Files/Directories)
Description:
Deletes files or directories.
Command: rm file.txt
Example Output:
(No output, file deleted)
6. cat (View File Content)
Description:
Displays content of a file.
Command: cat file.txt
Example Output: Hello Linux!
7. grep (Search Text)
Description:
Searches for a specific word or pattern in files.
Command: grep "Linux" file.txt
 Example Output: Hello Linux!
8. chmod (Change Permissions)
Description:
Changes file permissions.
Command: chmod 755 script.sh
Example Output: (No output, permissions changed)
9. ps (Process Status)
Description:
Shows currently running processes.
Command: ps
Example Output:
PID   TTY          TIME CMD
1234  pts/0    00:00:01 bash
5678  pts/0    00:00:00 ps
10. netstat (Network Statistics)
Description:
Displays network connections and ports.
Command: netstat -tuln
Example Output: tcp   0   0 0.0.0.0:80   0.0.0.0:*   LISTEN
11. ifconfig (Network Configuration)
Description:
Shows network interface details.
Command: ifconfig
Example Output: eth0: inet 192.168.1.10  netmask 255.255.255.0
12. ping (Check Network Connectivity)
Description:
Tests connection to another host.
Command: ping google.com
Example Output: 64 bytes from google.com: icmp_seq=1 ttl=117 time=20 ms
13. whoami (Current User)
Description:
Displays the logged-in user.
Command: whoami
Example Output: kali
14. sudo (Superuser Do)
Description:
Runs commands with administrative privileges.
Command: sudo apt update
Example Output:
[sudo] password for kali:
Reading package lists... Done
15. man (Manual Pages)
Description:
Displays help documentation for commands.
Command: man ls
Example Output:
LS(1) User Commands
NAME
       ls - list directory contents
Conclusion: These 15 Linux commands are fundamental for working in a Linux environment. They help users efficiently navigate the system, manage files, monitor processes, and troubleshoot network issues. Mastering these commands is essential for cybersecurity professionals, developers, and system administrators.

